Architects have understood that offices also need day care
The administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would say that he also hides inside a small nursery with everything he owns at such facilities: walls of colors, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outside terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design's employees can come to her.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, whose studio came from many well-known buildings in Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guard.
About 90 people work in the company, mainly in the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, daycare is one of the benefits Arch.Design your workers in the framework of your social program.
Constructors and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of their children.
The mini-guardia was an idea of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-guardia is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment, as well as the Czech State budget.
Thanks to the funding provided (more than 2.8 million Czech kroner) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified staff and services.
When funding is exhausted (two years), Arch.Design has an obligation to maintain the mini-guardia with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and in the submission of the request for funding contributed the Economy Rating company.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified staff; moreover, a nurse and teacher of the Ministry of Education are present all day, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since it is a "mini-guardia", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of the parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the contents of the mini-guardian programme are comparable to the usual pre-school curriculum.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach up to English.
The class not only has toys and table games, but also has a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go and see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the sign companies that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced the marketing of staff.
The bone house continues to fascinate after 100 years. Watch Gaudí interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade that reminds the scales and the omnipresent gently curved lines, all of this is typical of Antoni Gaudí's secession.
The cover of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and fauna.
By paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought order is observed.
At night, the whole facade of the house looks even more impressive, as it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentea and torsion of shapes continue to surprise us also inside.
The wavy wood copies the frames of the windows, the rails, the ornaments of the doors, the mirrors and the signposts.
The Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample neighborhood in the number 43 of the lively commercial street of Passeig de Gràcia, emerged from the refurbishment of a house in 1877 of architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on overthrowing the former building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Batlló House, made up of several apartments, did not design it by itself Antoni Gaudí.
In the design, architect Josep María Jujol collaborated.
In fact, in his plans of the project, ornaments appeared for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and mosaics used on the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Mila and the Park Güell de Gaudí, in which there are other pieces of it.
Because of its organic form, the premises soon after its completion called it "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of the boisterous."
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, appears the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí projected in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
It may be surprising its inclination of forty-five degrees.
During construction, Gaudí did not respect the rules of construction of the moment and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the outset, although the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were evidently so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city was so impacted with the result it requested to be corrected.
He was upset, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather: just fifteen days after the city's application, Joseph Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery of the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The house, with six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all the angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the doors of the salons and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the necessary privacy for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, obtained not only a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and swallows.
The game with the two colors brings maximum light on all the floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that the white reflects more light than the dark colors, which instead absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit the Batlló House, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house you will find the most spacious and more charged apartment available to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and expanded visits to the common area and to the bohardilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of the entrance to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entry of other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to enjoy the true atmosphere of the bed with your lizard towers, you should quickly become friends with some resident of the neighboring houses and visit you at home.
