More and more parents use monitoring devices to control their children
Fear for children leads more and more people to think of controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for the monitoring of vehicles, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, to the disappearance of the nine-year-old girl Anička Janatková.
At the moment the device has the approximate size of a cabinet box, but will soon be reduced to the size of a clock.
Many people were afraid of the missing Anička case and began to inform about the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
"We all try to say that it is not a matter of spying, but of another way to reduce the chances of a tragedy happening," says Petro Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I recognize that in certain cases such devices can be abused, for example if they get into someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not yet met such cases."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," Pilin adds.
In their opinion, children should always know what the "cajita" is for and how it is used in the event of an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns that if the child does not want to take it, he will just throw it away.
"Even younger children show great creativity when intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid being controlled."
"In the past, parents relied heavily on mobile phones, but these could be turned off as easily as the tracking device," Bočková says.
In his view, it is questionable whether such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
"If this is a prepared kidnapping, the author will almost always check whether the child wears some kind of electronic device that can reveal his location."
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices expands, you will also look for them, as your sale will no doubt be made with much publicity."
"In such cases, offenders always go one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, it adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised pedophile attack.
According to Robert Čech of the RC Monitoring company, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is destroyed immediately, its presence can help.
"The device can be configured to send the position regularly after a certain period."
"If you suffer damage, you will at least facilitate the last position of the person in question."
"The most expensive devices include a tilt meter, so if the person simply slips away and remains motionless, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," Čech says.
In your opinion, such a service can be obtained even with smart mobile phones with navigation, in which only special software should be installed.
The problem with the current tracking units is that for the moment they are devices with a size similar to a set of bezels or smaller mobile phones.
So they can get lost.
