Can civicism lay a bridge to unite the divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invective and negativity, a little civilism has been triggered this week in Washington.
Is it a premonition of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and the leaders of Congress did not produce any progress on the major issues to be dealt with during the outgoing session.
But as they all say, it was at least a polite discussion of the differences between the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, instead of being another empty episode to win partisan points.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the President's deficit commission was also civilized, despite the political differences between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates the members.
That is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both parties are now in a trial period, testing each other to identify signs of cooperativeism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
The reason why the meeting on Tuesday and subsequent assessments of the meeting by the participants was made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and are very deeply rooted to suggest any rapid change in the climate that existed over the past two years.
Whether taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance are involved, the two parties are in opposite poles.
However, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with regard to the way things are said," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the elections.
Elections arouse partisan passions, which are then extinguished.
That's good."
In some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing meeting, the Republicans and Democrats had no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are won at the end of the year, and nobody's in favour of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment subsidies, probably because the Republicans cannot make them believe they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, denying the unemployment subsidy for the unemployed.
After the meeting on Tuesday in the White House, there is greater optimism for possible treatment of these items during the outgoing session, together with the ratification of the new START Nuclear Disarmament Pact (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation in the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continuous bipartisanism when the new 112nd. Congress meets in January.
He said, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable, that a period of disagreement should begin.
"After the things that must be done are carried out, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to a confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civicism can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as an essay for the 2012 main event," he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters of the Tea Party, which contributed decisively to its creation.
As the Republican leaders are more aware of the dangers of overstating their position, they know that they must try to fulfill their promises to cut down state spending and annul the new health law.
These support lines are already clearly observed in initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include tax reform and the increase in some taxes and retirement age, and the reduction of expenditure.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken over one of the most difficult work in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forced the issue of deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the commission of 18 members to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the officers elected on the panel, suggesting that there are at least currently few bases or wishes for commitment in tax matters.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the White House Republicans and the Congressmen.
The first will happen next year in the form of partisan shocks, when Republicans challenge Obama on the budget, taxes and medical assistance, followed by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks he is losing will probably change course and seek compromise.
However, this can be an optimistic vision.
Partyism and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at their time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will take much more effort on both sides to find common points on issues that still divide them.
