Known as the "Carnicero" for its brutality during the Red Jemeres government, the commander continues to be popular in this remote fortress of the Red Jemeres in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructures, and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Red Jemers surrendered to the government, the long-held loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to face publicly those who had participated in the regime.
