A Global Plan to Renew Lighting
Yesterday, the UN has proposed in Cancún a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in one hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GEI) by almost one third of the additional decrease to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of major concrete projects that the UN expects to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, would be replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, even better, by bulbs of electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), much of the 1,800 million tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet would be avoided to illuminate humans.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the planetary car park.
In Copenhagen, last year, major issuing countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that should decrease global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of this amount should be reduced to stabilise, by 2020, the two-degree temperature increase in order to prevent it from being uncontrolled.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates in heat form and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, energy consumption is further reduced twice as much.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which allows us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the substitution plan that would be applied in a hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also operate with reostates and emit very little heat.
Above that, they contain nothing of mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluocompact bulbs, since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers provide instructions.
However, the report states, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact bulbs, but the thermal coal plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that is spilled with incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report details the advantages that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save one billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, i.e. equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost 2.5 billion.
