Avenger hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it unveils an apparent scandal, a scandal that just seems to scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound international changes and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file created by a secret service (independent of the nation to which it belongs) is exclusively made up of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and the sinisterly ridiculous profile of Khadafi has long given Cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret records should only be formed by news of public knowledge is essential for the dynamics of secret services, not just in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to the occult not only trust what they already know, which confirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or anxious) the head of secret services (if he could not be, I know, libération editor), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the U.S. Embassy of Rome to the State Department was the same as the Newsweek published the previous week.
Why, then, have the revelations of these files caused such a revolt?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that the embassies, at least since World War II and since Heads of States can call on the telephone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic role and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have become spy centers.
Any viewer who sees research films knows perfectly, we just pretend we don't know it by hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact of repeating it publicly infringes the duty of hypocrisy and gives a poor image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that a hacker would be able to consult the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "verks".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Previously, at the time of Orwell, he could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true ever since, being able to control every move thanks to the phone, every transaction made, hotel visited, autotrack taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power be endured that can no longer even keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel once said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public realm; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the network, as it would be like publishing it in a poster on the streets.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, confidential telephone conversations cannot be expected.
Nothing is easier than to find out whether and when a Head of State has moved by plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How can private and confidential relations be maintained in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my prediction is a science fiction thing and therefore novelist, but I imagine government agents moving discreetly on uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, as a matter of fact, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
This information is then preserved, in a single copy, in locked drawers: in the end, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is now advancing like a crab, that is, backward.
A century after the wireless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a telegraph with wires (telephones).
Video tapes (analogs) had allowed film researchers to study a movie step by step, moving forward and backwards, discovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now the CDs (digitals) only allow to move forward or back from chapter to chapter, i.e. to huge proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travels that it takes, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing but normal that the communication policy and techniques take us back to the horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was secretly uprooted in the embassies.
Currently, it is the embassies who request confidential information from the press.
Climate: France's hats in its financing promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unblocked (called early or fast-start) funding promises made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French hats have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed itself to contributing EUR 7.2 billion in three years and France EUR 1.260 million (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of the COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a great complementary event, the distribution of leaflets...
The transparency operation was appreciable and appreciated for what it really was worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2010 €2.2 billion, which puts it on the right track towards fulfilling its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But, if we look at the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudging official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each one chooses the best reference.
For example, the European Commission has taken as a reference the year 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added over three years for fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditure of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), while claiming to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the division between donations and loans.
Once again, there is no standard and each one who chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, believe that each euro lent amounts to one euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to the reduction of emissions based on more efficient technologies), it is clear to present a euro that is going to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated ... At most, only the cost of the loan should be calculated for its commitments for the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France does not find such reasoning useful: "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5% of loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (EUR 36.1 million); see the EU document to see it for its own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union that so frequently uses the loan.
Germany uses it by 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union makes a euro to fulfil its commitment, France only brings 10 cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
That's a good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending only EUR 36.1 million, he gets the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has taken over arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why were the other Member States to continue to donate when they can just lend?) and in negotiations, since developing countries are not foolish...
The chapter on early financing is a relatively short-term detail in relation to all climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra grains of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn early funding from this first year.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could move discussions on the stakes in connection with long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is with others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive at Cancún next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of the "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to advance negotiations.
